-- Field Journal pen: Ilkka Rautio (Cabins & Saunas desk). Summer 2026 batch.
insert into public.blog_posts (
  slug, title, kicker, excerpt, category_slug, tags, hero_image, hero_alt,
  content, author_id, author_snapshot, status, published_at, featured,
  read_time_minutes
) values (
  'the-sauna-thermometer-said-eighty-two',
  'The sauna thermometer said eighty-two',
  'Kemijärvi · July · Cabins',
  'One July evening at a lakeside cabin, told in sauna rounds: the two-hour fire, the birch whisk, the walk down the dock, and the exact temperature of a Lapland lake at midnight.',
  'cabins',
  ARRAY['sauna','mokki','kemijarvi','lake','summer']::text[],
  '/images/summer-lake-sauna-1200.webp',
  'Lakeside wooden sauna and dock at dusk, still water reflecting a pale bright midnight sky',
  '[{"type":"paragraph","text":"A wood sauna does not switch on. It is convinced. The one at the cabin I had borrowed on a lake near Kemijärvi takes, by long family consensus recorded on a note taped inside the woodshed door, two hours to convince — one hour of real fire and one hour of settling, during which the heat stops being in the stove and starts being in the room. The note is in pencil, in three different handwritings, and ends with the sentence: do not hurry the stones. I have decided this is the best sentence ever written about saunas and possibly about anything."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"So at eight in the evening I split birch logs in the yard, and at half past eight I lit the stove, and then I did what the sauna hour is secretly for: nothing, on the porch, with a book I did not read. The smoke came up out of the chimney pipe in a thin grey line and went straight up, because the evening was dead calm, and the lake lay flat as a sheet of tin all the way to the far shore."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"An honest accounting of my one mistake"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"This column has a rule that every entry includes the mistake, so here it is, early, where it belongs. When I lit the stove I left the damper half closed, because the previous user had left it that way and I assumed the previous user knew the stove. Within four minutes the sauna was full of smoke and I was standing in the doorway flapping a towel like a man signalling a rescue aircraft. The damper handle is the unpainted one on the left. Open it all the way when lighting. The previous user, I learned later by text message, knew the stove perfectly well and had closed the damper after their last fire precisely so the warmth would not escape up the chimney overnight. Everyone in this story behaved correctly except me."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"By ten the thermometer on the wall said eighty-two degrees, which on this particular wall, in this particular sauna, is the family number. Every sauna has a number. Nobody negotiates the number. Eighty-two on that thermometer — which may or may not agree with any other thermometer in Finland, calibration being a private matter between a sauna and its owners — means the stones are ready and the arguing can stop."},{"type":"pullquote","text":"Do not hurry the stones. Pencil, inside the woodshed door, three generations of handwriting."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Rounds"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"A proper evening sauna is measured in rounds, and a round has four movements: the heat, the whisk, the lake, and the porch. You sit on the top bench until the heat has found every part of you and your thoughts have slowed to roughly the speed of the steam. You throw water on the stones — löyly, the word for the steam and for something less translatable underneath it — and the heat arrives in a soft wave that makes everyone in the room exhale at the same time."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The whisk is a bundle of young birch branches, leaves on, tied at the handle — vasta up here, vihta in the southwest, and there are households in which this vocabulary question has outlasted marriages. Mine had been soaking in a bucket of warm water since the fire was lit. You slap yourself with it, shoulders and back and legs, not hard, and the whole sauna fills with the green smell of a birch forest after rain. It looks absurd and feels like the reason the tree was invented. Then the lake."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The walk down the dock is its own ceremony and must not be rushed or, worse, run. Bare feet on warm boards, steam coming off your shoulders into the cool air, and around you the enormous pale silence of a July night that is not dark and will not be getting dark. I made myself do the thing you must do, which is walk down the ladder rather than dive, because the body needs three seconds of decision at each rung. The lake in the second week of July, after a warm fortnight, was — I checked with the thermometer that lives on a string tied to the dock, because this column deals in numbers — seventeen degrees. Cold enough to make you swear quietly on entry. Warm enough to stay in, floating on your back, watching a sky that could not decide between ten in the evening and four in the morning."},{"type":"image","src":"/images/summer-lake-sauna-1200.webp","alt":"Lakeside wooden sauna and dock at dusk, still water reflecting a pale bright midnight sky","caption":"Between rounds, around midnight. The lake said seventeen degrees. The sky said nothing about the time.","full":true},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Sauna notes for cabin guests"},{"type":"list","items":["Ask about the damper, the number, and the house rules before your first fire, and believe the answers. Every sauna is a small sovereign state with its own constitution.","Give a wood sauna two hours from match to first round. If you are in a hurry, you are not ready for a sauna anyway.","Soak the birch whisk in warm water for at least an hour. A dry whisk is a bundle of sticks; a soaked one is medicine.","Drink water on the porch between rounds, more than feels necessary. The lake does not count as hydration, whatever it feels like.","Walk down the ladder rung by rung on the first swim. You can dive on the second, when the lake and your body have been introduced.","Rinse the benches, refill the water buckets, and leave the stove as the note tells you to. The next person inherits your manners.","Sit on the porch afterwards until you are fully dry and slightly cold. This last stage feels optional. It is the entire point."]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The fourth round"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"There is a state you reach somewhere in the fourth round that Finns do not talk about much, possibly because talking about it would be like explaining a joke. The heat and the cold have alternated enough times that your body has given up predicting and simply reports sensations without commentary. You sit on the porch bench with a towel around your shoulders and water dripping off the end of the dock, and the lake has gone so still that the far shore hangs upside down beneath itself, and a diver — the bird, kuikka, somewhere out in the middle distance — makes that long liquid call that sounds like the lake asking itself a question."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I locked the sauna at one in the morning, laid the whisk on the stones to dry into next time, and walked up to the cabin through grass already going grey with dew. Behind me the chimney was still breathing its last thin line of smoke into the bright night. The thermometer, I noticed through the little window, had begun its slow honest descent from eighty-two. It would take until morning to finish. Nobody was going to hurry it."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Written from the cabin porch near Kemijärvi at half past one in the morning, hair still damp, lake still silent, damper — for the record — properly closed."}]'::jsonb,
  NULL,
  '{"handle":"ilkka","display_name":"Ilkka Rautio","avatar_url":null}'::jsonb,
  'published',
  '2026-07-06'::timestamptz,
  false,
  8
)
